an extraordinary authority and popularity. However, it contained a number of revolutionary and innovative features that were in conflict with existing social and theological conventions. This book analyses all relevant texts from the 3rd to 5th centuries in which Perpetua and her comrades are mentioned, and demonstrates the ways in which these texts strive to normalize the innovative aspects of the Passio Perpetuae. These efforts, visible as they are already on careful examination of the passages of the editor of the passio, continue from Tertullian to Augustine and his followers. The normalization of the narrative reaches its peak in the so-called Acta Perpetuae which represent a radical rewriting of the original and an attempt to replace it by a purified text, more compliant with the changed socio-theological hierarchies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChristian martyrs in literature. 0aChristian martyrsxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aChristian saintszAfrica, NorthxBiographyxHistory and criticism. 0aChristian women martyrszAfrica, NorthxHistory. 4aActa Perpetuae. 4aAugustinus, Aurelius. 4aMärtyrerakten. 4aPassio Perpetuae et Felicitates. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aActa Perpetuae.  aAugustine.  aPassio Perpetuae et Felicitatis.  amartyrdom.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2015z9783110438727oZDB-23-DGF0 cEPUBz97831104188110 cprintz978311041942940uhttps://doi.org/10.